body:
Some people find it surprising that some iterator methods consume the iterator,and cannot be called in a loop:

```rust
fn stairs<T>(input:&[T])->Vec<Vec<T>>
where
    T:Clone
{
    let mut iter=input.iter().cloned();
    let mut ret=Vec::new();
    let mut size=1;
    loop {
        let inner=iter.take(size).collect::<Vec<_>>();
        if inner.is_empty() {
            return ret;
        }else{
            ret.push(inner);
            size+=1;
        }
    }
}
```

```
error[E0382]: use of moved value: `iter`
 --> src/main.rs:9:19
  |
5 |     let mut iter=input.iter().cloned();
  |         -------- move occurs because `iter` has type `std::iter::Cloned<std::slice::Iter<'_, T>>`, which does not implement the `Copy` trait
...
9 |         let inner=iter.take(size).collect::<Vec<_>>();
  |                   ^^^^ value moved here, in previous iteration of loop

```

It would be good to suggest calling `.by_ref()` for by-value iterator methods that don't always exhaust all iterator items.
